DESCRIPTION:***********\nDescription\n***********\n\nYou have been hired by
  the National Security Agency (NSA). For your first assignment (classified
 \, of course) you are to write a program to perform Caesar's Cipher\, a se
 cret message system designed by Julius Caesar about 2000 years ago. This m
 ethod essentially "adds 3" to each letter of the message. For example\, th
 e encrypted version of the message "Hi Mom" would be "Kl Prp".\n\n \n\n 
 \n\nYour program should ask the user for a message to encrypt\, and then i
 t should print the encrypted version of that message using Caesar's Cipher
 .\n\n \n\nSample Run\n\nBelow is an example of what your program may look
  like. \n\n \n\n      Welcome.  You know what to do.\n\n \n\n    
   Input ::  Hi Mom\, how are you?\n\n      The encrypted form of you
 r message is\n\n      Kl Prp\, krz duh brx?\n\n      Thank you for
  using this classified program.\n\n \n\nNote that spaces and punctuation 
 are not changed\, and case is preserved.\n\nAt least one function must be 
 present and used.\n\n \n\nEncrypting Letters\n\nSuppose C is a character 
 variable that holds one letter of the message. To encrypt C\, you must add
  3:\n\n    C = C + 3\;\n\n \n\nNote that if C holds an 'x'\, 'y'\, or '
 z' (or the uppercase equivalent) then you need to perform wraparound\, whi
 ch you can do by subtracting 23 instead of adding 3. For example\, if you 
 add 3 to 'y'\, you obtain '|' (the vertical bar). In this case\, you must 
 subtract 23 instead to obtain 'b'.\n\n \n\n*******\nHand In\n*******\n\nT
 urn in a listing  of your program\n\nThe program must have at least ONE f
 unction present to get full credit.\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n*****************
 *************\nExtra Credit (up to 14 points)\n***************************
 ***\n\nHere are several chances to earn extra credit.\n\n \n\n \n\n* Ins
 tead of reading the message from the user\, have the message come from a f
 ile whose name is supplied by the user. Also\, write the encrypted version
  of the message to an output file. Again\, let the user supply the filenam
 e. You may assume the file holds exactly one line of text. \n(4 points E.
 C.)\n\n \n\n* Allow the user to choose either encryption or decryption\, 
 and improve your program so that it can perform either one. \n(2 points E
 .C.)\n\n \n\n* Allow the user to pick a number other than 3 to add to eac
 h letter. For instance\, the user may wish to add 5 instead\, or maybe 10.
  This is sometimes called the encryption key. If you did part 2 above\, y
 ou must support decryption with a key other than 3 as well. \n(2 points E
 .C.)\n\n \n\n* This last improvement is more involved. Recall from the Gu
 essing Game Program that once a seed is chosen\, the "random" numbers are 
 always the same. We can take advantage of this to make decryption very dif
 ficult without knowledge of the key.  \n\nThe idea is this. The key is n
 ow the seed value for the random number generator\; use this seed to gener
 ate a series of random numbers between 0 and 25\, and use a different numb
 er to encrypt each letter of the message. (So you'll use srand(key)\; to
  initialize the generator.)\n\nModify your program to use this method for 
 encryption and decryption. \n(6 points E.C.)\n\nIf you successfully do th
 e last extra credit option\, you automatically get credit for parts 2 and 
 3\, thereby earning a total of 10 points.\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n*****\nNote
 s\n*****\n\n* Please remember to format properly (header in program\, inde
 nts\, separate lines\, naming\, etc). Remember to indent properly.\n\n* St
 art early!\n\n* Get the basic program working before trying any of the ext
 ra credit.\n\n* Must have at least one function in your program\n\n \n\n
