DESCRIPTION:Note:  The due date for this project is 4/27 (the last day of
  class) at midnight.  But\, we will hold our tournament during class on 4
 /27\, so if you want to participate\, you have to have a working version b
 y class time.\n\n \n\nObjective:  To practice using GUIs and Event-Driv
 en Programming\n\n \n\nSubmit:  Please submit:\n\n* Your program (the .j
 ava file). \n\n* A brief description of how your program chooses its move
 s.\n\nPlease put both of these things in a single document and upload th
 e document to Canvas. \n\n \n\nCollaboration:  You may work alone\, or
  in a group of two or three.  If you work with someone make sure everyone
 's names are in the comments\, and you may submit one copy of your program
 .\n\n \n\nDescription:\n\nYou are to write an interactive Java program th
 at plays Jerry-Tac-Toe with a human user.\n\nThis game is similar to Tic-T
 ac-Toe. The players\, X and O\, take turns making moves\, and the first to
  place three of their symbols in a row wins. If neither wins and all place
 s are filled\, the game is a draw.\n\nThe difference between standard Tic-
 Tac-Toe and Jerry-Tac-Toe is that the board is different (see pic). Here y
 ou can get three in a row using 1-2-3\, 1-5-9\, 1-4-8\, 2-4-7\, and so for
 th. 2-5-8 is not a winning combination (there is no line)\, and neither is
  2-4-8 (the line is not straight).\n\n \n\n[jtt.jpg] (https://butler.inst
 ructure.com/courses/54110/files/5423388/preview)\n\n \n\n \n\nSpecifics:
  \n\n* The user should be allowed to choose whether to go first or second
 .\n\n* Your program should draw the board on the screen and draw the moves
  graphically. You can have the user specify moves either by entering the n
 umbers of the positions (with buttons or a textfield) or by using the mous
 e.\n\n* When someone has won or all 9 places are filled\, the game should 
 stop and declare the outcome.\n\n* The user should have the option to star
 t a new game or quit.\n\nPlease also note that\, to receive full credit on
  this assignment\, it is not necessary for your program to play well\; it 
 is sufficient for it to play legally.\n\n \n\nFinal Tournament:\n\nDuring
  the last day of class\, we will hold a Jerry-Tac-Toe tournament.  The wi
 nner of the tourney will receive 10 extra credit points. Each program will
  play each of the other programs twice (moving first and second). The prog
 ram with the best win-loss record after playing everyone is declared the w
 inner. (Wins count for 2 points\, ties for 1 point.) If there is a tie\, t
